{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514251"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12306"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12306"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.1,0.18,0.54,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4826"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92844"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1722"},{"type":"tags","id":"1932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department (ED) with a three day history of severe throat pain which is particularly worse on swallowing. On further questioning she states that she has had the \u0022chills and sweats\u0022 but denies chest pain, cough or coryza.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, the patient is in obvious discomfort, leaning forward with her mouth open. She has a cup full of saliva and has a hoarse voice. She is mildly tachycardic at 110/min and febrile at 38.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn direct examination, her uvula is midline and her posterior oropharynx is moderately hyperaemic with no evidence of tonsillar enlargement or exudate. A lateral X-ray of the neck exhibits marked oedema of the prevertebral soft tissues and absence of the vallecula space.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Quinsy","Pharyngitis","Ludwig\u0027s angina","Epiglottitis","Croup"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in the above stem is likely suffering form \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiglottitis, \u003C/strong\u003Ean airway threatening inflammatory condition of the epiglottis, periglottic and aryepiglottic folds. The most frequently linked organism with this condition is \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae \u003C/em\u003Etype B (Hib), for which most people receive immunisation at a young age. Clinical features of epiglottitis include a prodromal period of a few days of lethargy before the patient may go on to develop dysphagia, odynophgia, drooling, stridor and a high fever. Lateral neck X-ray often exhibits a swollen epiglottis obliterating the vallecula (also known as the \u0027thumbprint sign\u0027).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Equinsy \u003C/strong\u003E(or pertonsillar abscess) may present with clinical features similar to that of epiglottitis. Symptoms and signs of note to assist in differentiating between the conditions are that the uvula may be deviated from midline, cervical lymphadenopathy is prominent and trismus may be present. A neck X-ray may demonstrate excess prevertebral swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELudwig\u0027s angina \u003C/strong\u003Eis a form of severe diffuse cellulitis that affects the floor of the mouth and often spreads rapidly and bilaterally and may go on to affect the submandibular, sublingual and submental spaces resulting in a state of emergency. Common clinical features includes trismus, neck swelling and fever\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to inflammation of the pharynx and tonsils, is common in all age groups and is most often secondary to a viral infection. For bacterial causes, \u003Cem\u003ES. pyogenes \u003C/em\u003E(group A, \u03b2-haemolytic strep) is the most common cause (5%-15%) in adults. Patients present with erythematous tonsils, tonsillar exudates, enlarged and tender anterior cervical lymph nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECroup \u003C/strong\u003E(tracheolaryngobronchitis) is a common respiratory illness generally seen in children aged 6 months to 3 years and rarely seen after age 6 years. Uncommon complications may include bacterial tracheitis, pneumonia and pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute epiglottitis requires prompt diagnosis and intervention as it may threaten the airway"],"references":["Abdallah C. Acute epiglottitis: Trends, diagnosis and management. Saudi J Anaesth. 2012 Jul;6(3):279-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23162404/","Sizar O, Carr B. Croup. [Updated 2022 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available atfrom: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431070/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92844"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12306"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92844"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T08:39:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T08:39:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4826"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1254"},"attribute